<ArticleLayout
  title="Cleaning Product Storage: What to Check Before Buying Cabinets or Caddies"
  description="Before buying cabinets, caddies or baskets for cleaning products, check bottle height, leaks, access, ventilation, child and pet safety, moisture and laundry space."
  category="Laundry"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="8 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/laundry.webp"
  imageAlt="A practical laundry room with warm finishes, baskets and tidy everyday storage"
>
  <p>
    Cleaning products often end up in the laundry because it feels like the most practical
    place to keep them.
  </p>
  <p>
    Detergent, stain removers, sprays, cloths, gloves, brushes, mop heads, dishwasher
    tablets, floor cleaners, pet cleaning products and spare refills can all collect around
    the laundry tub, under the sink or on open shelves. Over time, the laundry can become a
    storage area for products that are half-used, duplicated, leaking or hard to reach.
  </p>
  <p>
    A new cabinet or caddy only helps after the product mix is clear: what gets used weekly,
    what leaks, what has expired, what should move rooms, and what needs to stay out of reach.
  </p>
  <p>
    A good cleaning-product storage system should make useful items easier to find and
    handle. It should not hide leaks, block access, create clutter or make products easier
    for children or pets to reach.
  </p>
  <p>
    For broader laundry planning, see our main guide:
    <a href="/guides/laundry-storage-what-to-measure-and-check-before-you-buy/">
      Laundry Storage: What to Measure and Check Before You Buy</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Start with the real cleaning-product problem</h2>
  <p>Work out what is causing the clutter before adding more storage.</p>
  <p>The issue may be:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>too many duplicate products</li>
    <li>empty or nearly empty bottles</li>
    <li>products stored in several rooms</li>
    <li>sprays sitting around the laundry tub</li>
    <li>bottles too tall for shelves</li>
    <li>leaking containers</li>
    <li>cloths and brushes mixed with chemicals</li>
    <li>products stored where children or pets can reach them</li>
    <li>no clear place for daily-use products</li>
    <li>refills taking over cupboard space</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Different problems need different storage choices.</p>
  <p>
    If the issue is duplicate products, a new caddy may not help. If bottles are too tall for
    the shelf, a shallow basket will not solve the problem. If products need to move between
    rooms, a portable caddy may be more useful than a fixed cabinet.
  </p>
  <p>The first step is to sort what is already there, then store only the products that still earn their place.</p>

  <h2>Remove old, empty and duplicate products first</h2>
  <p>Cleaning-product storage works better when the collection is reduced first.</p>
  <p>Take everything out and group similar items together before choosing an organiser.</p>
  <p>Check for:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>empty bottles</li>
    <li>products you no longer use</li>
    <li>duplicate sprays</li>
    <li>old cloths</li>
    <li>worn gloves</li>
    <li>leaking bottles</li>
    <li>broken brushes</li>
    <li>dried-out wipes</li>
    <li>refills with no clear product match</li>
    <li>products that belong in another room</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Only keep products that have a clear use and a suitable storage place.</p>
  <p>
    If the laundry contains several half-used products that do the same job, storage may not
    be the real issue. The collection may need simplifying before another organiser is added.
  </p>

  <h2>Check product labels and storage instructions</h2>
  <p>Cleaning products should be stored according to their labels.</p>
  <p>
    Check whether any products have specific storage instructions before choosing a cabinet,
    caddy or shelf.
  </p>
  <p>Look for label guidance about:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>keeping containers closed</li>
    <li>storing away from children</li>
    <li>storing away from pets</li>
    <li>avoiding heat</li>
    <li>avoiding direct sunlight</li>
    <li>keeping products upright</li>
    <li>ventilation</li>
    <li>avoiding mixing products</li>
    <li>safe disposal if no longer needed</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This article does not replace product label directions. If a product gives specific
    storage instructions, follow those instructions.
  </p>
  <p>
    A storage product should support safe storage. It should not be treated as making
    unsuitable storage safe.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure bottle height</h2>
  <p>Bottle height is one of the most common storage issues.</p>
  <p>Measure the tallest products you use before choosing shelves, baskets or caddies.</p>
  <p>Check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>laundry detergent bottles</li>
    <li>stain remover sprays</li>
    <li>floor cleaners</li>
    <li>disinfectant bottles</li>
    <li>bleach or specialist cleaners if used</li>
    <li>refill bottles</li>
    <li>spray trigger height</li>
    <li>pump bottle height</li>
    <li>glove or brush storage height</li>
  </ul>
  <p>A shelf may look useful but fail if the bottles do not stand upright.</p>
  <p>
    If products need to lie down to fit, there may be a higher risk of leaking. Upright
    storage is usually more practical for liquids and sprays.
  </p>

  <h2>Check cabinet and shelf depth</h2>
  <p>Cleaning products are often awkward because bottles vary in shape.</p>
  <p>For a cabinet, basket or shelf, measure:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>shelf depth</li>
    <li>shelf width</li>
    <li>internal cabinet height</li>
    <li>door opening width</li>
    <li>hinge clearance</li>
    <li>whether bottles can be removed easily</li>
    <li>whether items at the back are visible</li>
    <li>whether the organiser can be cleaned</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Deep shelves can hold more, but products at the back are easy to forget. Shallow shelves
    are easier to see but may not hold bulk refills.
  </p>
  <p>
    For small laundries, avoid storage that makes the room harder to move through. For
    small-space planning, see:
    <a href="/guides/small-laundry-storage-what-to-check-before-buying-organisers/">
      Small Laundry Storage: What to Check Before Buying Organisers</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Think about access and frequency</h2>
  <p>Not every cleaning product needs to be stored in the same place.</p>
  <p>Group products by how often they are used.</p>
  <p>Daily or weekly items may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>laundry detergent</li>
    <li>stain remover</li>
    <li>cleaning spray</li>
    <li>cloths</li>
    <li>gloves</li>
    <li>dishwashing or laundry-related products</li>
    <li>pet clean-up products if used regularly</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Less frequent items may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>spare refills</li>
    <li>specialist cleaners</li>
    <li>seasonal cleaning products</li>
    <li>extra cloth packs</li>
    <li>backup bottles</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Frequently used items should be easy to reach. Less-used products can live higher,
    further back or in a separate storage area if that is safe and practical.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid putting everyday products in a place that requires moving several items every time
    laundry is done.
  </p>

  <h2>Choose between a cabinet, caddy, basket or shelf</h2>
  <p>Different storage types suit different problems.</p>

  <h3>Cleaning caddies</h3>
  <p>Cleaning caddies are useful when products are carried between rooms.</p>
  <p>They may suit sprays, cloths, gloves and brushes used together.</p>
  <p>Check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>handle comfort</li>
    <li>bottle height</li>
    <li>base stability</li>
    <li>cleaning ease</li>
    <li>whether it becomes too heavy when full</li>
    <li>where it will live when not in use</li>
  </ul>
  <p>A caddy is less useful if it becomes a dumping ground for every product in the laundry.</p>

  <h3>Open baskets</h3>
  <p>Open baskets can group products on shelves or inside cupboards.</p>
  <p>They are simple, removable and easy to reposition.</p>
  <p>
    Check whether the basket is easy to wipe clean and whether bottles can stand upright.
  </p>
  <p>Avoid baskets that hide leaks or make products hard to see.</p>

  <h3>Closed cabinets</h3>
  <p>Closed cabinets can make a laundry look tidier and may help keep products out of sight.</p>
  <p>Check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>internal shelf height</li>
    <li>door swing</li>
    <li>ventilation</li>
    <li>whether the cabinet can be cleaned</li>
    <li>whether it needs wall fixing</li>
    <li>whether it suits a rental</li>
    <li>whether products remain easy to inspect</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Closed storage should not hide leaking or expired products.</p>

  <h3>Under-sink organisers</h3>
  <p>Under-sink organisers can help if the laundry tub cabinet is dry and accessible.</p>
  <p>
    Check pipe clearance, moisture, cabinet height, door opening width and whether the
    organiser blocks access to plumbing.
  </p>
  <p>Avoid storing moisture-sensitive items under the tub if the space is damp.</p>

  <h3>Wall shelves</h3>
  <p>Wall shelves can help when floor space is limited.</p>
  <p>
    Check wall material, load needs, fixing requirements, reach height and rental
    restrictions.
  </p>
  <p>Heavy bottles should not be stored so high that they are difficult to lift down safely.</p>

  <h2>Consider children, pets and access</h2>
  <p>Cleaning products need careful storage.</p>
  <p>Consider who can reach the storage solution.</p>
  <p>Check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>whether children can access the storage area</li>
    <li>whether pets can reach or knock over products</li>
    <li>whether products are stored low or high</li>
    <li>whether doors or lids close properly</li>
    <li>whether bottles can tip or leak</li>
    <li>whether products are stored according to their labels</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Do not assume a basket, caddy or cabinet makes products safe by itself.</p>
  <p>
    If child or pet access is a concern, use storage that supports safer handling and follow
    the relevant product instructions.
  </p>

  <h2>Check for leaks and spills</h2>
  <p>Cleaning products can leak, drip or leave residue.</p>
  <p>Check whether the storage area is easy to inspect and clean.</p>
  <p>Useful features may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>wipeable surfaces</li>
    <li>removable trays</li>
    <li>smooth bases</li>
    <li>moisture-resistant materials</li>
    <li>enough light to see spills</li>
    <li>easy access to the back of the shelf</li>
    <li>products stored upright</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Avoid absorbent baskets or fabric organisers for bottles that may leak.</p>
  <p>
    A tray or removable basket can make it easier to clean small spills before they spread
    across a cabinet or shelf.
  </p>

  <h2>Think about ventilation and moisture</h2>
  <p>
    Laundries can be damp, especially in small rooms, laundry cupboards and bathroom-laundry
    combinations.
  </p>
  <p>When choosing storage, consider:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>whether the laundry feels damp</li>
    <li>whether there is airflow</li>
    <li>whether products sit near wet towels</li>
    <li>whether the cabinet traps moisture</li>
    <li>whether shelves are easy to wipe</li>
    <li>whether fabric or timber organisers are suitable</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Moisture can make some storage materials harder to maintain.</p>
  <p>
    In damp areas, smooth, wipeable and removable storage is usually more practical than
    fabric baskets or untreated timber.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep cleaning cloths and brushes separate</h2>
  <p>Cloths, sponges and brushes can make cleaning-product storage messy.</p>
  <p>Consider separating:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>clean cloths</li>
    <li>used cloths waiting for washing</li>
    <li>gloves</li>
    <li>brushes</li>
    <li>mop heads</li>
    <li>spray bottles</li>
    <li>detergent</li>
    <li>refills</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Wet cloths and brushes should not be buried in a closed basket with bottles.</p>
  <p>If items need to dry, they may need airflow before being put away.</p>
  <p>This is especially relevant in small laundries where moisture can build up quickly.</p>

  <h2>Common cleaning-product storage mistakes</h2>
  <p>
    Cleaning-product storage can become frustrating when products are organised before they
    are sorted.
  </p>
  <p>Common mistakes include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>buying a caddy before removing duplicate products</li>
    <li>choosing shelves that are too short for bottles</li>
    <li>hiding leaks in deep cupboards</li>
    <li>storing products where children or pets can reach them</li>
    <li>keeping old products with no clear use</li>
    <li>mixing damp cloths with bottles</li>
    <li>using absorbent baskets for liquids</li>
    <li>storing heavy bottles too high</li>
    <li>buying a cabinet that blocks a walkway or door</li>
    <li>ignoring product label storage instructions</li>
  </ul>
  <p>The goal is not to store more products. The goal is to store useful products clearly and safely.</p>

  <h2>When not to buy cleaning-product storage yet</h2>
  <p>You may not need new storage yet if the real issue is excess products.</p>
  <p>First check whether the laundry contains:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>empty bottles</li>
    <li>old sprays</li>
    <li>duplicates</li>
    <li>products used once and forgotten</li>
    <li>refills for products no longer used</li>
    <li>leaking bottles</li>
    <li>worn cloths or brushes</li>
    <li>items that belong in the kitchen, bathroom or garage</li>
  </ul>
  <p>If removing these items clears the shelf or cupboard, a new organiser may not be necessary.</p>
  <p>
    Sometimes the better first step is simply keeping fewer products and giving the regular
    ones a clear home.
  </p>

  <h2>Simple cleaning-product storage checklist</h2>
  <p>Before buying cabinets, caddies or baskets for cleaning products, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>What products do I actually use?</li>
    <li>Have I removed empty and duplicate bottles?</li>
    <li>Do product labels give storage instructions?</li>
    <li>Have I measured the tallest bottles?</li>
    <li>Will bottles stand upright?</li>
    <li>Is the storage easy to clean?</li>
    <li>Can leaks be seen and wiped quickly?</li>
    <li>Is the area damp or poorly ventilated?</li>
    <li>Will children or pets be able to access products?</li>
    <li>Is the product suitable for a rental if needed?</li>
    <li>Will it block doors, machines, tubs or walkways?</li>
    <li>Would sorting products solve the issue first?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Cleaning-product storage works best when it is simple, visible and easy to maintain.</p>
  <p>
    Sort the products first, follow label directions, measure the space, and choose a simple
    home for the items you actually reach for.
  </p>

